HEADWORD: Euthanasia
<hw>Eu`tha*na"si*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr.
<?/; <grk>e'y^</grk> well + <?/ death, <?/, <?/, to die: cf. F.
<ets>euthanasie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An easy death; a mode of
dying to be desired.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An <xex>euthanasia</xex> of all
thought.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hazlitt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The kindest wish of my friends is <qex>euthanasia</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>the act or process of putting to death for humane
purposes; -- used to refer to the killing of animals in order to relieve
or avoid pain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Euthanasy</ent>⟦br⟧
